  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 11.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - With this verse the answer to Solomon's prayer begins. It is here concisely given in two verses, but occupies five (vers. 10-14) in the parallel place, including the verse not found here, which says, \"The speech pleased the Lord, that Solomon had asked this thing.\" Otherwise there is no essential difference of any importance, though it may be noted that the parallel gives voice to the promise of \"length of days,\" on the condition of Solomon fulfilling his part in showing obedience to the Divine will, and in following the steps of his father. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Riches, wealth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "עשֶׁרנְכָסִים",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The most elementary idea of the former of these two words seems to be \"straight growth,\" \"prosperity;\" of the latter, \"to gather together\" or \"heap up.\" The former is found first in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 31:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and in the verb (hiph. conjugation) in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 14:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Afterwards it is found in almost all of the historical books, in the Psalms, Proverbs, Ecclesiastes, and in the prophets Jeremiah and Daniel. The latter word occurs only five times (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 22:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; in this and the following verses; and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ecclesiastes 5:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ecclesiastes 6:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Its Chaldee form is also found in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 6:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and Ezra 7:26. A comparison of these passages scarcely sustains the supposition of some, suggested by the derivation of the word, that it marks specially those stores of useful things which constituted largely the wealth of Old Testament times. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Wisdom and knowledge",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The distinction between these is evident, as also that they are needful complements of one another for the forming of a catholic, useful, sound character. 2 Chronicles 1:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The divine promise. Here עשׁר is strengthened by the addition נכסים, treasures (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 22:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ecclesiastes 5:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ecclesiastes 6:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). תּשׁפּט אשׁר, ut judicare possis. In general, the mode of expression is briefer than in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 3:11-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the conditional promise, \"long life\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 3:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), is omitted, because Solomon did not fulfil the condition, and the promise was not fulfilled. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 1:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " לבּמה is unintelligible, and has probably come into our text only by a backward glance at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 1:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", instead of מהבּמה, which the contents demand, and as the lxx and Vulgate have rightly translated it. The addition, \"from before the tabernacle,\" which seems superfluous after the preceding \"from the Bamah at Gibeon,\" is inserted in order again to point to the place of sacrifice at Gibeon, and to the legal validity of the sacrifices offered there (Berth.). According to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 3:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Solomon, on his return to Jerusalem, offered before the ark still other burnt-offerings and thank-offerings, and prepared a meal for his servants. This is omitted by the author of the Chronicle, because these sacrifices had no ultimate import for Solomon's reign, and not, as Then, supposes, because in his view only the sacrifices offered on the ancient brazen altar of burnt-offering belonging to the temple had legal validity. For he narrates at length in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 21:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 21:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". how God Himself directed David to sacrifice in Jerusalem, and how the sacrifice offered there was graciously accepted by fire from heaven, and the threshing-floor of Araunah thereby consecrated as a place of sacrifice; and it is only with the purpose of explaining to his readers why Solomon offered the solemn burnt-offering in Gibeon, and not, as we should have expected from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in Jerusalem, that he is so circumstantial in his statements as to the tabernacle. The last clause of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 1:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"and he was king over Israel,\" does not belong to the section treating of the sacrifice at Gibeon, but corresponds to the remark in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 4:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and forms the transition to what follows. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]